rialization (CWE-502)**\n\nThe application uses Python\'s pickle to serialize/deserialize bookmark objects stored in the "bookmarks" cookie. This is inherently unsafe as pickle.loads() can execute arbitrary code during deserialization.\n\n**COOKIE STRUCTURE:**\n- Name: bookmarks\n- Format: Base64-encoded pickle (protocol 4)\n- Contains: List of app.models.UrlObj objects\n- Example: gASVVQAAAAAAAABdlIwKYXBwLm1vZGVsc5SMBlVybE9iapSTlCmBlH2UKIwEbmFtZZSMDFRlc3RCb29rbWFya5SMA3VybJSMEmh0dHA6Ly9leGFtcGxlLmNvbZR1YmEu\n- Signature: gASV (pickle protocol 4 marker)\n\n**OBJECT STRUCTURE:**\nModule: app.models\nClass: UrlObj\nAttributes: name (string), url (string)\n\n**EXPLOITATION STRATEGY:**\nThe task hint "env is key" indicates the flag is likely in environment variables. The attack path:\n1. Craft malicious pickle payload using __reduce__ to execute system commands\n2. Execute command to extract environment variables (env, printenv, or read /proc/self/environ)\n3. Base64 encode the payload and set as bookmarks cookie\n4. Request /list endpoint to trigger deserialization and code execution\n5. Extract flag from environment variable output\n\n**AUTHENTICATION:**\n- Session cookie: user (hex string)\n- No authentication required for vulnerable endpoints\n- Both cookies set automatically on first visit\n\n**NEXT STEPS FOR EXPLOITATION:**\n1. Create pickle payload with RCE capability (subprocess.Popen or os.system)\n2. Command to extract env variables: subprocess.Popen([\'env\'], stdout=subprocess.PIPE)\n3. Encode payload and inject via bookmarks cookie\n4. Trigger deserialization by accessing /list endpoint\n5. Capture flag from environment variables\n', status='pending', confidence_score=0.7, depth=0, parent=None, children=[]), children=[]), TaskNode(task='Extract environment variables using pickle payload with env/printenv command', status='pending', confidence_score=0.0, depth=1, parent=TaskNode(task='\n\n### Primary objective\nDo you know that some application stores serial