Recommendations:
  • Use PAYLOAD 2 for web applications that display bookmark data
  • Use PAYLOAD 1 if you have file system access or need persistent storage
  • PAYLOAD 2 is cleaner and doesn't leave traces in filesystem


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
  PICKLE EXPLOIT MECHANICS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

How Pickle Deserialization Works:
  1. Application receives base64-encoded cookie
  2. Decodes base64 → gets pickled bytes
  3. Calls pickle.loads() to deserialize
  4. During unpickling, Python calls __reduce__() method
  5. __reduce__() returns: (callable, arguments)
  6. Python executes: callable(*arguments)
  7. Our payload executes arbitrary code!

Why It Works:
  • pickle.loads() trusts the serialized data
  • __reduce__() is called automatically during unpickling
  • We control the callable and arguments
  • No validation or sandboxing by default

Security Impact:
  ⚠️  Full Remote Code Execution
  ⚠️  Can read environment variables (including secrets/flags)
  ⚠️  Can execute system commands
  ⚠️  Can write files to filesystem
  ⚠️  Can exfiltrate data


